text: I’m pleased to be the Republican member on the first House Congressional Delegation visit to China in 6 years. The US-China economic relationship is critically important and China is the state of Washington’s number one export market. However, the most important part of reestablishing Congressional dialogue with the highest levels of the Chinese government revolves around US national security interests. I appreciate US Ambassador to China David Purdue for inviting us to Beijing and Chinese Premier Li Qiang for the frank and honest conversation about the challenges and opportunities in the US-Chinese Relationship. It is vitally important that China allow increased regular direct communication between its military and the US military, that it take immediate steps to curb the flow of fentanyl into America and that it partner with the US to help bring the Russia-Ukraine conflict to a close and keep Iran from nuclear proliferation.

The assassination of Charlie Kirk is a sad and tragic day for America. Many members of Congress knew him well and know his wife and children. I did not know him well, but did have the opportunity to sit with him at a dinner a few years ago in Spokane. I found Charlie Kirk good natured and friendly and admired his openness to debating ideas and his good work to get young people involved in politics and policy making. I also admired that while he was out talking about his own political views, he was always open to debate and giving the microphone and a platform to those folks that disagreed with him. Political violence and murder of a public political personality is terrible for our country. It should be rejected by everyone, both elected officials and all Americans. May Charlie Kirk rest in peace and may his memory be a blessing. 🇺🇸
May Charlie Kirk Rest in Peace 🙏

Latest update - the Big Beautiful Morning continues. Under House Rules, the Speaker, the Majority Leader and the Minority Leader are the 3 members who get special “magic minute” privileges to speak as long as they want on a Bill. D Minority Leader Hakeem Jeffries is currently using his “minute” to speak agains the OBBB and the expectation is that - similar to how Corey Booker got a little notoriety for setting the “filibuster” length of speaking record record in the Senate earlier this year - that Jeffries is attempting to beat the current 8hr House  record by R Kevin McCarthy. If so he’ll be speaking for about 3hrs more. It’s mainly just performative and he’s certainly telling a few fibs about the Bill, but it’s a fun part of the feisty American Congressional governance process in action. (It’s also a little therapeutic for many of the D’s who thought they’d beaten the Bill last night before the “Republican 4th Quarter Comeback”)  As the old saying goes: “The majority gets to decide what passes, the minority gets to decide how long it takes.”
As such, with some time on our hands, rather than watch Hakeem’s performance, I came back to the office to do a little work and may go hit up the House gym to shoot a few hoops while we wait. Also, some fun Washington state Congressional history in this video about the “ugly baby chicken painting” that gets handed down to new members of Congress from our state. (Thank you to all of you back home who have dropped me notes to mention that you are enjoying these video updates. I’ll try to do a few more today as things progress.) 🇺🇸

Eleanor and I are saddened to learn of the passing of Pope Francis. We join Catholics across Eastern Washington and around the world in prayer—for the Holy Father’s soul, and for the Church in this time of mourning and transition. May He rest in peace.
 
Pope Francis was a voice of compassion and moral clarity in a world too often divided. While I never met Pope Francis, as someone who lived and worked for a year as a volunteer with the Jesuit community of Beira, Mozambique after college, I often found myself reflecting on his time as Pope as framed by the works and teachings of his fellow Jesuits.

His deep commitment to the poor, to peace, and to the dignity of every human life left a profound mark on our time. Eleanor and I join with Catholics in Eastern Washington and around the world in prayer as we mourn his passing.

I was pleased to join a rally in support of Ukraine as the country defends itself from Russia’s repeated attacks on civilian population centers and urge the return of Ukrainian children kidnapped by Russian forces. While I agree that it is in the US strategic interest to bring the war to close and that far too much of the generous US aid to the country has been wasted by corruption, there should be no sugar coating who Putin is and the human deveststion he has wrought. The US can’t continue to subsidize lazy EU nations who don’t want to fund their own basic defense, but we also must remain vigilant and realistic about the increased likelihood of WW3 if Putin successfully gets troops on the Polish border. America now faces the most complex and dangerous set of international challenges since 1945. It is vital that the US be both respected and feared on the international stage. After the bumbling of the last 4 years, I’m optimistic and hopeful that under President Trump’s leadership we can rebuild American military and diplomatic supremacy and thereby ensure a more peaceful world. 🇺🇸
